Step 1: Prepare Data

The goal is to select statistically similar zip codes in LA county and at least one other county.

Prepare data

Load standardized data with response rates (already QA’d for MBC reports), load the Black HTC index and call HTC-related ACS data via api.

# load standardized, summarzied data and pull out zip code estimates
stand_data <- fread(paste0(wcl_root, "My Black Counts/standardized_data.csv"), stringsAsFactors = FALSE, data.table = FALSE,
                  colClasses = c("GEOID"="character", "zip"="character"))

# query only zip code summaries
stand_data <- 
  stand_data %>% 
  filter(level =="zip code" & county_name %in% c("Los Angeles", "Alameda")) %>% 
  select(-c(gq_pop_pct, diff, REGION, Turf_final, BLKHTC_num, BLKHTCCA, housecur, resp10, resp20_10_diff, blackhh_prc_cv)) %>% 
  mutate(blackhh_prc = blackhh/tothh)


### Load Black HTC Data ###
# these are all rates at the tract level, instead of raw numbers that I can summarize, unfortunately. Maybe I can average tract rates in the zip ?
htc <- read.dbf(paste0(wcl_root, "My Black Counts/BlackHTC/BLKHTC_final/BLKHTC_final.dbf"), as.is = TRUE)
htc <- htc[,c(5, 24:39, 41)]

# convert all character cols to numeric
htc_dat <- 
htc %>% 
  mutate_at(c('popchng', 'newres', 'vacunits', 'multunit',
                    'nobrdbnd', 'renter', 'yngadlt', 'fborn', 'blwpov', 'unemp', 'male', 'child', 'comphh', 'noncit', 'arrests',
                    'voters', 'BLKHTC_num'),as.numeric)

Prepare ACS data

# get some new stats
# internet B25003B
# poverty B17001B
# multiunit B25032B
# immigrants B05003B

# variables for foreign born
immigvars <- subset(v18, name %like% "B05003B" & label %like% "Foreign born" & !label %like% "Foreign born!!" )
immigvars <- immigvars$name

# vars for multiunit housing
multiunvars <- subset(v18, name %like% "B25032B" & !label %like% "!!2" & !label %like% "!!1" & !name %like% "_001" ) 
multiunvars <- multiunvars$name

internetvars <- subset(v18, name %like% "B28009B" & name %in% c("B28009B_005", "B28009B_006")) 
internetvars <- internetvars$name

blackvars <- 
list( 
# get tract data
    immig = get_acs(geography = "tract", state="CA", county = c("037", "001"), variables = immigvars, summary_var = "B05003B_001",
                    survey = "acs5", year=2018) %>% 
      mutate(level = "tract", 
             var = "foreign born"),
    
    internet = get_acs(geography = "tract", state="CA", county = c("037", "001"), variables = internetvars, summary_var = "B28009B_001",
                    survey = "acs5", year=2018) %>% 
      mutate(level = "tract", 
             var = "internet"),
    
    rent = get_acs(geography = "tract", state="CA", county = c("037", "001"), variables = "B25003B_003", summary_var = "B25003B_001",
                    survey = "acs5", year=2018) %>% 
      mutate(level = "tract", 
             var = "renter"),
    
    pov = get_acs(geography = "tract", state="CA", county = c("037", "001"), variables = "B17001B_002", summary_var = "B17001B_001",
                    survey = "acs5", year=2018) %>% 
      mutate(level = "tract", 
             var = "poverty"),
        
    multiun = get_acs(geography = "tract", state="CA", county = c("037", "001"), variables = multiunvars, summary_var = "B25032B_001",
                    survey = "acs5", year=2018) %>% 
      mutate(level = "tract", 
             var = "multiunit"))


# summarize vars that need it (ie foreign born)
blackvars <- lapply(blackvars, function(x) x %>% 
                      group_by(GEOID, level, var) %>% 
                      summarize(est = sum(estimate, na.rm=T),
                                est_moe = moe_sum(moe, estimate, na.rm = T),
                                tot = mean(summary_est, na.rm=T),
                                tot_moe = mean(summary_moe, na.rm=T)))

Zip-tract crosswalk

  • This crosswalk has been QA’d for previous versions of MBC reports

  • Zip data source: ESRI 2018 (W:/Base/esri/2018/esri_zip_code_poly_ca.shp)

  • First, intersect zip codes and counties–a zip has to have at least 10% of its area in the county for it to be assigned to that county.

  • Second, intersect zips and tract. Where the most of a tract’s area is (i.e. which zip code) is the tract-zip assignment. This is to avoid duplicating tracts, and creates a continuous, non-overlapping representative zip code layer. I didn’t do any proportional allocation of tract demographics because that seems like adding extra assumptions and error on top of already-problematic zip codes.

# export tract-city-zip-county crosswalk
tract_final_df <-  fread(paste0(wcl_root, "My Black Counts/geometry_id_tract_crosswalk.csv"), 
                         stringsAsFactors = FALSE, data.table = FALSE,
                         colClasses = c("COUNTYFP"="character", "GEOID"="character", "ZIP_CODE"="character"))

Join the Black HTC data to the zip code crosswalk

# only do this for LA County and Alameda county--going to focus in on oakland and la
htc_zip_mean <- 
tract_final_df %>% 
  select(GEOID, COUNTYFP, ZIP_CODE, county_name, NAME) %>% 
  full_join(htc_dat, by="GEOID") %>%
  filter(COUNTYFP %in% c('037', '001')) %>% 
  
  # group by zip and get summaries of the Black HTC characteristics
  group_by(ZIP_CODE) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(popchng, newres, vacunits, multunit,
                    nobrdbnd, renter, yngadlt, fborn, blwpov, unemp, male, child, comphh, noncit, arrests,
                    voters, BLKHTC_num), mean, na.rm=T)

# summarize

Join the ACS var list to the tract-zip crosswalk

# collapse list
blackvars_df <- do.call("rbind", blackvars)
 
black_zip_summary <- 
# join crosswalk
blackvars_df %>% 
  left_join(tract_final_df, by="GEOID") %>% 
  
  #summarize by zip code
  group_by(ZIP_CODE, var) %>% 
  summarize(est = sum(est, na.rm=T),
            est_moe = moe_sum(est_moe, est, na.rm = T),
            tot = sum(tot, na.rm=T),
            tot_moe = moe_sum(tot_moe, tot, na.rm = T),
            prc = est/tot,
            prc_moe = moe_prop(est, tot, est_moe, tot_moe),
            prc_cv = (prc_moe/1.645)/prc) %>% 
  
  # keep only percentage for zip
  select(ZIP_CODE, var, prc) %>% 
  
  pivot_wider(names_from = var, values_from = prc) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(ZIP_CODE)) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

Join the summary variables to the standardized data with response rates

# join Black summary vars to the standardized data
dat <- 
stand_data %>% 
  select(zip, county_name, city, estimate, prc, resp20_old, resp20, blackhh, blackhh_prc, count_tract, count_htc ) %>% 
  
  # join black variable zip summary by zip code
  full_join(black_zip_summary, by=c("zip"= "ZIP_CODE")) %>% 
  
  # join the black htc mean by zip
  full_join(htc_zip_mean %>%  
              select(ZIP_CODE, BLKHTC_num) %>% 
              rename("mean_BLKHTC_num" = BLKHTC_num), 
            by=c("zip"= "ZIP_CODE")) %>% 
  
  # remove NA response records and where black hh are 0
  filter(blackhh > 0 & !is.na(resp20) & !is.na(mean_BLKHTC_num)) %>% 
 # format response rate percents as decimals
   mutate(resp20_old = resp20_old/100,
         resp20 = resp20/100,
         mean_BLKHTC_num = mean_BLKHTC_num/100)   # I want to convert to decimal without losing info about the range itself



test <- 
  dat %>% 
  group_by(zip, county_name) %>% 
  summarize(dup = n())

# los angeles county data
datk_la <- 
  dat %>%  
  filter(county_name =="Los Angeles" ) %>% 
  select(zip, blackhh_prc, `foreign born`, internet, multiunit, poverty, renter, mean_BLKHTC_num) %>%  # prc, resp20
   column_to_rownames(var="zip")
#head(datk_la)

# alameda county data
 # just remove the duplicate zips for now, but circle back later
datk_al <- 
  dat %>%  
  filter(county_name =="Alameda") %>%
  mutate(flag = ifelse(city %in% c("Oakland", "San Leandro", "Hayward"), 0.5, 0)) %>%  # the three cities with the highest black hh count/prc
  select(zip, blackhh_prc, `foreign born`, internet, multiunit, poverty, renter, mean_BLKHTC_num, flag) %>% # prc, resp20
  column_to_rownames(var="zip")

# head(datk_al)

Run k-mean cluster on LA zip codes

k = 5

  • note: The total within-cluster sum of square measures the compactness (i.e goodness) of the clustering and we want it to be as small as possible.(source)[https://uc-r.github.io/kmeans_clustering]
k5_la <- kmeans(datk_la, centers = 5, nstart = 25)

# total within cluster sum of squares
k5_la$tot.withinss # need to compare to other modesl
## [1] 18.08812
### Plot LA K-means clusters (k=7)  
fviz_cluster(k5_la, data = datk_la)

# look at group  (the group I've had my eye on anywyas)
names( k5_la$cluster[ k5_la$cluster==1]) 
##  [1] "90008" "90016" "90018" "90043" "90044" "90047" "90056" "90059"
